node.text:
Today is #BlackWomensEqualPayDay. According to @NPWF, if the #WageGap were eliminated, a Black woman working full time year-round would have enough for roughly:
👶🏾: 2.5 years of child care
🍲:156 more weeks of food
🏡:22 more months of rent

Of course, Black women aren’t alone in experiencing a wage gap, and many women are paid even less; Native American women are paid 60 cents, and Latinas are paid 55 cents for every dollar paid to white, non-Hispanic men.

While the wage gap is smaller for Black women in tech, it's still a problem. Our CEO, Dr. Tarika Barrett, offered advice for tech leaders on LinkedIn today (link in bio)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Girls Who Code in Google. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Girls Who Code @GirlsWhoCode Jul 16 Code Dr. Marian Croak's tech is behind Zoom and Skype calls. In fact, she has over 200 patents and is changing the face of tech.'.

node.text:
Did you know that a Black woman created the tech that makes zoom calls possible? 👩🏾‍🔬 Meet Dr. Marion Croak, a leader in tech who holds over 200 patents. Croak is known for developing VOIP (voice over internet protocol,) a vital part of our digital conversations.

Dr. Croak currently leads a new center of expertise on responsible AI within Google Research. For the past six years she’s been a VP at @Google working on projects like site reliability engineering and  bringing public Wi-Fi to India’s railroads

Currently, she helps the company responsibly develop AI that has a more positive impact on society. Who’s your STEM #WCW? Let us know in the comments below.

That’s one small step for man, one large step for women everywhere. 👩🏾‍🚀⭐️ 

Happy #MoonDay, a day celebrating the 52nd anniversary of the day the first man stepped on the moon. 🌕💫 While Neil Armstrong gets most of the credit, the true heroes behind the moon landing are these out of this world women in STEM. Today, (and every day tbh) we celebrate leaders like Katherine Johnson, Mary Jackson, JoAnn Morgan, and Margaret Hamilton.

node.accessibility_caption: Happy Independence Day and Fourth of July but remember everyone was free in 1776. Don’t forget about Juneteenth

node.text:
On July 4, we celebrate freedom. Or, at least, that's what most of us were taught. But the truth is, the Declaration of Independence — the anniversary of which is what we celebrate on Independence Day — didn't free all Americans when it was passed in 1776. It wasn't until almost 90 years later that the last enslaved African Americans learned they were free in 1865. We celebrated that day on Juneteenth, close to two weeks ago. 

So while freedom is a beautiful thing to celebrate, today (and every day), we're thinking not only about those who haven't always gotten the justice they deserve, but the many people — including the incredible girls in our programs — who believe in, and are working hard to create, a future in which everyone is free.
